{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480571"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:46:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:46:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"77"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"77","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/77"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.16,0.17,0.59,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"77"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98822"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"77","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/77"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"77"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81214"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44323"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98822"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of urinary frequency, dysuria and low-grade fever. She is 10 weeks pregnant with her first child. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. She denies any loin pain, abdominal cramps or vaginal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 115/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Urine dipstick shows leucocytes (3+) and nitrites (positive).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit for intravenous antibiotics","Oral ciprofloxacin for seven days","Oral trimethoprim for three days","Oral nitrofurantoin for five days","Await urine culture results before treating"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with an uncomplicated urinary tract infection (UTI) in early pregnancy. Due to the physiological changes of pregnancy and increased risk of complications, prompt treatment is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral nitrofurantoin\u003C/strong\u003E for five days is the most appropriate first-line treatment. It is safe in early pregnancy and has good efficacy against common urinary pathogens. The recommended dose is 100mg four times daily. However, nitrofurantoin is not recommended close to delivery (after 37 weeks\u0027 gestation, or sooner if early delivery is planned) because it may increase the risk of neonatal jaundice and haemolytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral trimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided in the first trimester as it is a folate antagonist and may interfere with neural tube development. It can be considered in later pregnancy if other options are unsuitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is pregnancy category B3 and should be reserved for cases of proven resistance to first-line agents. There are safer alternatives available for this uncomplicated presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission for intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were signs of systemic illness, pyelonephritis, or sepsis. This patient is clinically stable with no features suggesting upper urinary tract involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAwaiting urine culture results\u003C/strong\u003E before treating would delay appropriate therapy unnecessarily. Given the presence of symptoms and positive dipstick findings, empiric treatment should be commenced promptly to prevent complications such as pyelonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing treatment, a repeat urine culture should be performed to confirm cure. If recurrent UTIs occur during pregnancy, prophylactic antibiotics and renal tract imaging may be indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nitrofurantoin is a suitable first-line antibiotic for urinary tract infection in early pregnancy.","Pregnant women with urinary tract infection require immediate antibiotic treatment due to high risk of complications.","Trimethoprim should be avoided in the first trimester of pregnancy due to folate antagonism."],"references":["McCormick T, Ashe RG, Kearney PM. Urinary tract infection in pregnancy. The Obstetrician and Gynaecologist 2008;10:156-162. Available at: https://obgyn.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1576/toag.10.3.156.27418","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Urinary tract infection and bacteriuria in pregnancy. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2025 [cited 2025 Apr 16]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Kenyon S, Pike K, Jones DR, Brocklehurst P, Marlow N, Salt A, Taylor DJ. Childhood outcomes after prescription of antibiotics to pregnant women with spontaneous preterm labour: 7- year follow-up of the ORACLE II trial. Lancet 2008; 372:1319-27. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18804276/","Ghouri F, Hollywood A, Ryan K. Urinary tract infections and antibiotic use in pregnancy - qualitative analysis of online forum content. BMC Pregnancy Childbirth. 2019 Aug 13;19(1):289. Available at:https://doi.org/10.1186/s12884-019-2451-z"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81214"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"77"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81214"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-17T18:43:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-17T18:44:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"77"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98822"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty